		<title>Science and myth&#8230;</title>
		<link>https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/535</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Mark]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 05 Aug 2012 18:44:08 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Cambridge]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Mobile]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Music]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/535</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I&#8217;ve built up a number of interesting links and videos over the last few months that relate to some extent to science, myth or both. A range of these are briefly described and embedded or linked to in this post &#8230; <a href="https://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/535">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve built up a number of interesting links and videos over the last few months that relate to some extent to science, myth or both. A range of these are briefly described and embedded or linked to in this post &#8211; I hope you enjoy!</p>
<p>The video below shows <a href="http://www.theverge.com/2012/6/21/3101918/watch-this-projection-tech-inside-99-year-old-dome-poland">a pretty cool use</a> of advanced 3D modelling and projection technology.<br />
<iframe loading="lazy" src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/41486619?portrait=0&amp;color=bababa" width="560" height="334" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></p>
<p>Tomorrow morning, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_Science_Laboratory">NASA&#8217;s Curiosity Rover</a> will attempt to land on Mars. This involves a range of technical challenges which must work correctly, during this first real test, for the rover to make it to the surface in a working state &#8211; the video below gives an exciting overview of the difficulties involved.<br />
<script type="text/javascript" src="http://cdn-akm.vmixcore.com/vmixcore/js?auto_play=0&#038;cc_default_off=1&#038;player_name=uvp&#038;width=560&#038;height=332&#038;player_id=1aa0b90d7d31305a75d7fa03bc403f5a&#038;t=V0klYOaUyJ5RL3Go9w5dZzumrSYmccwIHo"></script><br />
<span id="more-535"></span><br />
The <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aquarius_(laboratory)">Aquarius Lab</a> is one of the few underwater research facilities in the world dedicated to science. Recently it was visited by a reporter who made a short video about the facility and the lives of the &#8220;aquanauts&#8221; on board.<br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/gj6frb_mHzQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>Google and Tate Modern recently unveiled an interesting art project called This Exquisite Forest, explained in the video below. <a href="http://www.exquisiteforest.com/">You can visit the website</a> to take part yourself, if you want.<br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/nnhJ1841K-8" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>A photographer stitched together images taken from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Space_Station">the International Space Station</a> into an incredible video: &#8220;View from the ISS at night&#8221;.<br />
<iframe loading="lazy" src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/45878034" width="560" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></p>
<p>In other recent news, <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-wiltshire-18550513">Stonehenge may have been built to unify</a> the native inhabitants of Great Britain and <a href="http://www.engadget.com/2012/07/16/htc-hd2-gets-unofficial-android-4-1-jelly-bean-port/">the HD2 continues to be one of the most versatile smartphones in history</a>.</p>
<p>Now the entertainment section! The first of the two videos below was recorded in Cambridge and is a rather amusing portrayal of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Batman">The Dark Knight</a> in real life. The second is particularly well made (I like the way the whole thing is done without colour) and is both amusing and scary at the same time.</p>
<p><strong>Batman &#8211; The Dark Knight&#8230;in real life</strong><br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/AfgtEjjQnHQ" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Dark Midnight: Bet of a Lifetime</strong><br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/ux5C3V9sFwA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>The trailer for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doctor_Who_(series_7)">the upcoming series of Doctor Who</a> was recently released and, for the first time in a while, features music from the show rather than music by <a href="http://www.g400.co.uk/cantabits/archives/298">Two Steps from Hell</a>.<br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/qrEUBl2pacU" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>Finally, below is some music I have found recently and liked &#8211; some related to the theme of this post, some not. Of particular note is an interesting orchestral arrangement incorporating several songs by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Eyed_Peas">The Black Eyed Peas</a>. Also, from the excerpts I&#8217;ve heard, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Dark_Knight_Rises_(soundtrack)">the soundtrack of The Dark Knight Rises</a> sounds good.</p>
<p><strong>The Avengers Theme (Alan Silvestri) Piano Arrangement</strong><br />
<iframe loading="lazy" width="560" height="315" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/eCd09oj35GA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Black Eyed Peas &#8211; Orchestral Cover HD</strong><br />
